<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910809-0012</DOCNO><DOCID>910809-0012.</DOCID><HL>   Nynex Unit Ex-Head   Is Accused by SEC   Of Insider Trading</HL><DATE>08/09/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><CO>   NYN</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><NS>SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)</NS><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- The Securities and Exchange Commission accusedthe former president of a Nynex Inc. unit of insider tradingin connection with Nynex's 1990 takeover of StockholderSystems Inc.   In a lawsuit filed in federal court in Manhattan, the SECalleged that Albert M. Harris, former president of Nynex'sDisc Inc. unit, bought the stock in March 1990 based onconfidential information about the proposed takeover. OnApril 26, 1990, Nynex announced its plans to acquire thecomputer-software company for $60 million.</LP><TEXT>   The SEC alleged that Mr. Harris sold his 6,000 StockholderSystems shares between April 26 and May 11, 1990, for a totalprofit of $36,250.   The SEC also accused Mr. Harris of telling hisbrother-in-law about the takeover proposal, and alleged thatthe brother-in-law made a profit of $2,925 by trading on theinformation. Mr. Harris's brother-in-law wasn't identified inthe complaint, and he wasn't named as a defendant.   The SEC asked the court to order Mr. Harris to turn overhis alleged insidertrading profit as well as hisbrother-inlaw's and to pay additional penalties totaling$117,525.   Gerson Mehlman, an attorney for Mr. Harris, said, &quot;Mr.Harris didn't do anything wrong.&quot; Mr. Harris, 55 years old,of Towson, Md., was president and chief executive officer ofDisc until January 1991.   The SEC alleged that Mr. Harris learned on Feb. 22, 1990,that Nynex and Stockholder Systems were discussing how muchwould be paid for the company. The suit alleged that Mr.Harris bought the Stockholder Systems shares on March 12,three days before the takeover proposal was scheduled to bepresented to the Nynex board.   The complaint said that Mr. Harris was told specificallythat information about the proposed takeover wasconfidential.   A spokesman for Nynex said the company learned of the SECinvestigation last year and has fully cooperated withinvestigators. He said Mr. Harris's employment contractexpired last Dec. 31 and wasn't renewed.</TEXT></DOC>